    "active_paradigms": [
      {
        "idea": "Inhibitor-modulated lag via time-shifted autocatalytic Knowles kinetics \u2014 apply the Langmuir gate to the lag/nucleation timing rather than only the growth rate",
        "description": "Restructure the RHS so the inhibitor primarily lengthens the lag phase (the crossing-timing the shape loss measures) instead of only scaling secondary flux. Keep the mass-conservation capacity (plateau - c) as a squared-positive plateau c7**2 to prevent negative-capacity runaway. Define smooth_state = sqrt(c**2 + eps**2). Let the autocatalytic term be gated by BOTH surface occupancy AND monomer: secondary = c5**2 * monomer * smooth_state**2 * gate, where gate = 1/(1 + c1**2*cd)**2 (squared Langmuir so high doses strongly delay). Add a monomer-fed primary term c2**2*monomer and elongation c3**2*(seed + c4**2*c). Crucially, multiply the ENTIRE positive growth by an inhibitor-delayed activation 1/(1 + c6**2*cd) applied uniformly so onset time (not just late rate) is pushed later, matching 10-25% crossing times on inhibited curves. Drop the separate sink term to cut constants from 11 to ~8, improving fit stability. expression = capacity * (primary + elongation + secondary) / (1 + c6**2*cd). Set initial_values with small positive seeds for c1,c6 so cd=0 recovers the uninhibited limit exactly.",
        "what_to_optimize": "shape_loss_val (lag-time crossing accuracy on inhibited curves) and combined_score via fewer, better-conditioned constants",
        "cautions": "Keep all rate constants as squares (c_i**2) so they stay positive and cd=0 exactly reproduces uninhibited dynamics. Ensure eps=c0**2 is nonzero to keep sqrt differentiable. Verify plateau uses c7**2 to bound capacity. Fewer constants (8) reduces overfitting risk on 15-setting design.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.symbolic_ode_template"
      },
